S&P 500 Stock RNN Project!

Context

Stock market data is fascinating to analyze to me, and strong predictive models can have large financial payoffs. The biggest theme is that, finding a well-structured dataset covering a wide array of companies can be challenging for many of the times given!

Our dataset provides historical stock prices for the last 5 years for all companies currently listed on the S&P 500 index.

Content

The dataset is available in two formats to suit various use cases:

  1. all_stocks_5yr.csv: A single merged file containing stock data for all companies.
  2. individual_stocks_5yr: A folder containing individual CSV files labeled by stock ticker name.

Columns in the Dataset

Each file includes the following columns:

  • Date: Date in the format yy-mm-dd.
  • Open: Price of the stock at market open (in USD).
  • High: Highest price reached in the day.
  • Low: Lowest price reached in the day.
  • Close: Closing price of the stock (in USD).
  • Volume: Number of shares traded.
  • Name: The stock's ticker symbol.

Let us dive into our data and uncover the trends driving the S&P 500 shall we!

Model Design & Architecture Overview:

Our Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) uses:

  1. LSTM Layers:

    • Capture sequential dependencies in stock price data over time!
    • You will see that later on we are experimenting with three activation functions: Sigmoid, Tanh, and ReLU.

  2. Stacked Architecture:

    • 3 LSTM Layers:
      • Layer 1 & 2: Return sequences for capturing deep temporal patterns ...
      • Layer 3: Then, this layes outputs a compressed feature vector for prediction ...

  3. Dense Output Layer:

    • Single neuron for predicting the normalized closing price ...

Key Features:

  • Sequence Length: 30 timesteps.
  • Feature Input: 1 feature (Normalized closing price).
  • Output: Predicted next days closing price.
In[73]:
# defining our window size first ...
window_size = 30

# creating a function to call the and create our sequences
def create_sequences(data, window_size):
    X, y = [], []
    for i in range(len(data) - window_size):
        X.append(data[i:i+window_size]) 
        y.append(data[i+window_size])  
    return np.array(X), np.array(y)

# we will get an input-output sequences here 
X, y = create_sequences(rnn_data['close'].values, window_size)
print("Shape of X:", X.shape)
print("Shape of y:", y.shape)

# now we are designing our RNN ...
model = Sequential([
    LSTM(64, activation='tanh', return_sequences=True, input_shape=(30, 1)), 
    LSTM(64, activation='tanh', return_sequences=True), 
    LSTM(32, activation='tanh'), 
    Dense(1) 
])

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')
model.summary()

Activation Functions Experimentation

  • Activation functions tested: Sigmoid, Tanh, ReLU
  • Observing performance differences across metrics.

Observations ~

  • Sigmoid: This function I feel like struggled to capture the fullest of complexity of our sequential data.
  • Tanh: Yet again, Tanh achieved the best performance with the lowest MSE and MAE! It also demonstrated stable validation loss and is well-suited for normalized sequential data.
  • ReLU: Less effective in handling this dataset, likely due to the risk of dying neurons when processing normalized values (potentially!).

activation_functions = ['sigmoid', 'tanh', 'relu']
my_results = {}

for activation in activation_functions:
    print(f"\nTraining Model with Activation Function: {activation}\n")
    
    model = Sequential([
        LSTM(64, activation=activation, return_sequences=True, input_shape=(30, 1)),
        LSTM(64, activation=activation, return_sequences=True),
        LSTM(32, activation=activation),
        Dense(1)
    ])
    
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])
    history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=25, batch_size=32, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), verbose=1)
    
    evaluation = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0, return_dict=True)
    mse = evaluation['loss']  
    mae = evaluation['mae']  
    
    my_results[activation] = {'MSE': mse, 'MAE': mae}
    
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label=f'{activation} - Train Loss')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label=f'{activation} - Validation Loss')

plt.title('Training and Validation Loss for Activation Functions')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

for activation, metrics in my_results.items():
    print(f"{activation} - MSE: {metrics['MSE']}, MAE: {metrics['MAE']}")

Some Observations on our given Activation Functions!

1. Sigmoid

  • MSE: 0.0023
  • MAE: 0.0383
  • It performed reasonably well but not as low as Tanh as we can see ....
  • Biggest Take: Suitable but may struggle to capture the full complexity of the sequential data.

2. Tanh

  • MSE: 0.0014
  • MAE: 0.0299
  • It achieved the best performance with the lowest MSE and MAE values! Wohoo!
  • Biggest Take: I feel like it worked well for our sequential data, especially since we also normalized values. This is likely because it centers outputs around zero...

3. ReLU

  • MSE: 0.0026
  • MAE: 0.0418
  • Tend to have higher errors compared to both Sigmoid and Tanh ...
  • Biggest Take: May not handle this normalized sequential dataset as effectively as Tanh as we can see!

Overall Analysis

  • Our Tanh activation function outperformed Sigmoid and ReLU! It ended up achieving the lowest Mean Squared Error (MSE) and Mean Absolute Error (MAE) as well! This is a good sign to us!
  • I feel like this also suggests that Tanh is better suited for this stock price dataset due to its ability to process normalized data centered around zero.
  • ReLU, while powerful in general as we've seen in some of my other projects, it still appears to be less effective for this specific task!

To do some further fine-tuning, I decided to go a bit further and test almost like a hybrid activation function setup ...

In this experiment, I'm going to use different activation functions in different layers of the LSTM model. I feel like this approach should leverage some of the strengths of multiple activation functions!
Tanh: For deeper sequential dependencies, especially in the initial layers!
ReLU: For capturing nonlinear relationships in later layers ...
Sigmoid: For compressing outputs when transitioning to the dense layer we have present ...

print("\nTraining Model w/ a Hybrid Activation Functions\n")

model = Sequential([
    LSTM(64, activation='tanh', return_sequences=True, input_shape=(30, 1)),  
    LSTM(64, activation='relu', return_sequences=True),                      
    LSTM(32, activation='sigmoid'),                                          
    Dense(1)                                                                 
])

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=25, batch_size=32, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), verbose=1)
evaluation = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0, return_dict=True)
mse = evaluation['loss']  
mae = evaluation['mae']

Some Key Findings from our Model Performance Visuals

Mean Squared Error (MSE):

  • Tanh: As we've seen, Tanh outperformed all other configurations with the lowest MSE, showcasing its suitability for our stock prediction task!
  • Adam Optimizer: Then, Adam showed us a really strong performance, achieving the second-lowest MSE, proving its effectiveness in optimization as well.
  • Hybrid Model: Gave us the highest MSE, indicating that combining activation functions was just not the most optimal thing to do for this dataset. We also saw this earlier!

Mean Absolute Error (MAE):

  • Tanh: Once again led w/ the lowest MAE, as the most reliable activation function in our experiments!! Wohooo!
  • ReLU: Displayed moderate (ehhh) MAE, indicating slightly less precision compared to Tanh ...
  • Sigmoid: Performed decently but most certainly lagged behind in accuracy as we also saw.

Project Wrap-Up! Final Conclusion

  • Our Tanh activation function delivered the best results with the lowest MSE and MAE. It demonstrated great stability and effectiveness overall for sequential stock price predictions!
  • Our Adam optimizer also proved us to be our most optimal and robust choice, as it achieved quick convergence and minimizing prediction errors as well!
  • In regards to our hybrid model, while exploratory, it definitely revealed that combining activation functions introduced more inconsistencies for this dataset of ours.
